author: Alistair McGeorge
title: Emily Ratajkowki 'targeted by hackers again with nude pictures touted for sale'
text:
Emily Ratajkowki 'targeted by hackers again with nude pictures touted for sale' It's said more private pictures have allegedly been stolen from the star's iCloud Share Get celebs   Thank you for subscribing!   
Emily Ratajkowski has allegedly been targeted by online hackers again and it's claimed nude pictures of the model have been touted for sale. 
Former Celebrity Big Brother housemate Helen Woods has claimed she has been sent over 200 images of the model and asked to publish them in her online column. 
Writing for the Daily Star, she said: "Last week, I was pondering along through life, when I received a DM on Twitter. No idea who this guy was, but had a peek all the same out of curiosity. Emily is said to have been targeted by hackers (Photo: Instagram/emily ratajkowski) The star has shared tasteful snaps on social media (Photo: Splash) 
“Turns out, it was a link to Emily Ratajkowski’s iCloud pictures. This clown inboxed me and asked that I release the full set of naked images in my column.” Read More 
Helen - who clarified that she disagreed with the invasion of privacy - said that the alleged images were "private stuff, sent between two people". Emily is yet to comment on Helen's column (Photo: Barcroft Media) She was targeted by hackers back in 2015 (Photo: Barcroft Media) 
Late in 2015, Emily spoke out about falling victim to hackers for the first time. 
She defended people who saw the images online, and put the blame on "the people that stole the photos". She hit out at the people who stole the photos (Photo: Instagram) The star is said to have allegedly been targeted a second time (Photo: Getty) 
Speaking to GQ magazine, she said: "A lot of people who were victims of that said anyone who looks at these pictures should feel guilty, but I just don't think that's fair. 
“I think once it's out there, it's out there, and I'm not sure that anyone who Googles it is necessarily a criminal. I think the people that stole the photos are." Like us on Facebook
